Does not exist: Assume for contradiction that such a data structure exists. We present a reduction to sorting. Given an array $a_1, a_2, \dots, a_n$ that we wish to sort, proceed as follows: first, if the totally ordered domain from which the array elements are drawn is $M$, extend the domain by adding a new maximal element $\infty$. The sorting algorithm is:
\begin{enumerate}
\item For $i = 1, \dots, n$: perform \texttt{insert}$((a_i, \infty))$ into the data structure.
\item For $i = 1, \dots, n$: print \texttt{left()} to the output of the sorted array and then delete it from the data structure using \texttt{delete()}.
\end{enumerate}
In total we performed $\Theta(n)$ operations \texttt{insert}, \texttt{left}, \texttt{delete}, all in amortized constant time, thereby yielding a sorting algorithm that performs $O(n)$ comparisons. A contradiction.

\textbf{Description of the data structure (DS):}
A perfect hash of the elements by their value. For each element, also store its rank (order statistic).

\textbf{Construction:}
Sort the array — $\mathcal{O}(n \log n)$ — to determine the rank of each element.
Insert the elements into a perfect hash in expected $\mathcal{O}(n)$.

\textbf{How to sort using the data structure:}
Look up the order statistic of each element in $S$. Sort $S$ by these order statistics using Counting Sort.

