\begin{proof}
Let $A$ be a dynamic data structure. We present a sequence of operations that allows sorting an array of size $n$:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Perform $n$ \textsc{Insert} operations.
    \item Repeat the following operation $n$ times: perform \textsc{FindMin}, print the element found, and delete it from the structure.
\end{enumerate}
This is a sorting algorithm, and it is clearly in the comparison model (since the structure is in the comparison model).
\end{proof}

The number of values in each list is bounded by the number of cells that must be read from the table (minus one, since an unsuccessful search requires reading an empty cell); therefore:
\begin{itemize}
\item Searching for an element from $X_1$ requires reading at most $k_1 - 1$ keys.
\item Searching for an element from $X_2$ requires reading at most $(k_1 - 1) + (k_2 - 1)$, i.e., $k_1 + k_2 - 2$ keys (if the lists are chained to the same cell).
\item Even searching for an element that is neither in $X_1$ nor in $X_2$ requires reading at most $k_1 + k_2 - 2$ keys, since this is the maximum list length.
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item Structure description: two order-statistic trees (balanced binary search trees with a size field in the nodes). One ordered by $x$ and the other by $y$. A pointer to the $\frac{n}{4}$-th element in $x$ and to the $\frac{3n}{4}$-th element in $y$.
\item Implementation of \texttt{insert} and running-time analysis: insert into both trees and perform \texttt{select} to update the pointers.
\item Implementation of \texttt{delete} and running-time analysis: delete from both trees and perform \texttt{select} to update the pointers.
\item Implementation of \texttt{isCentric} and running-time analysis: check the relation between the $x$ and $y$ values of the pointers.
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item Data structure description: a min-heap and a hash table with cross-pointers. The key is the segment length.
\item Implementation of Find-Min and running-time analysis: return the root of the heap (the heap’s min operation).
\item Implementation of delete and insert, and running-time analysis: on insertion, insert into the heap and into the table, and in the table update a pointer to the element’s position in the heap. On deletion, find the key in the hash table and, using the pointer, delete the element from the heap. Also delete it from the table. On insertion or deletion—if a position changes—update the pointer in the hash table.
\item Build procedure and running-time analysis: build a binary heap in linear time ($O(n)$). Insert each element into the hash table using \emph{chaining}, at the head of the list, and at the same time update the pointer to its position in the heap.
\end{itemize}
